## Decisions Made
- Chose broad `Bash(git notes:*)` allow over ref-scoped variants: Claude Code permission matching is prefix-based on the literal command, so commands with different argument orders would not match a ref-scoped allow. Future-proofs against Memento workflow argument changes.
- Added `Bash(git push origin refs/notes/commits:*)` as a separate allow entry: notes push is a distinct command from `git notes`, and the Memento workflow runs it after every commit.
- Applied CodeRabbit's jq conditional-merge diff verbatim over extracting to a helper script: smallest defensible change, no new maintained file.

## Problems Encountered
- batch-refine.yml emitted linear/slack/notion MCP server entries unconditionally even when the corresponding secret was empty: when only ANTHROPIC_API_KEY is configured, claude-code-action could pick an unusable server and fail. Resolved by jq object-merge with `if $secret == "" then {} else {...} end` per integration.
- Original `.claude/settings.json` allowed direct `Bash(sqlite3 .knowledge/vault.db:*)` which contradicts CLAUDE.md line 10 (no direct .knowledge/ reads). Already removed by the prior resolving-pr-blockers commit (32ef6ce); this commit only adds the Memento permissions.

## Constraints Identified
- Claude Code permission matching is literal-prefix on the command tail: ref-scoped allows like `Bash(git notes --ref=...:*)` only match when arguments appear in that exact order, making them fragile.
- The jq conditional-merge approach keeps construction inline as a single expression, but adds ~20 lines to the run block. Alternative (extract to scripts/build-mcp-config.sh) was rejected to avoid a new maintained file.

## Open Questions
- Should the Memento workflow's required permissions be documented in CLAUDE.md so future readers know why these allow entries exist?
- If the conditional-merge pattern is repeated in other workflows (mark-evidence, curate-report only have github / linear today), should this be factored into a shared helper at some point?

